Project Objective

The goal of the segmentation project is to determine optimal customers and their preferences for a company who wishes to build a “social entertainment app.” The customer preference data was taken from a survey of 1800 respondents.

The analysis uses kmeans clustering to group customers into clusters based on their responses to the survey questions.

Edit the dataframe

Feature engineering: consolidate q2 Q2 phone - combining “other” with phone types that no longer exist or are smaller brands Grouped brands with Other: Blackberry, Nokia, Windows Phone, HP/Palm

numfa <- numfa %>%
  mutate(q2ot = case_when(q2r4 == 1 | q2r5 == 1 | q2r5 ==1 | q2r6 ==1 | 
                            q2r7==1 | q2r9 == 1~ 1, TRUE ~ 0))

Preprocess dataframe: drop columns, drop NA

Drop unwanted columns: Respondents who don’t own a smartphone or use apps (Q2r10, q4r11), questions not listed on the survey (Q5), Q2 phone brands that were combined for q2ot, Q25 and Q26: psychographic questions not relevant to phone usage, social media or entertainment habits

Kmeans Clustering

#copy to new dataframe
cpnumft <- numft

# scale data before clustering
cpnumfta <- scale(cpnumft)

# elbow plot to find optimal k, use set seed to start with a random number
set.seed(123)

# function to compute total within-cluster sum of square 
wss <- function(k) {
  kmeans(cpnumfta, k, nstart = 10 )$tot.withinss
}

# Compute and plot wss for k = 1 to k = 15
k.values <- 1:15

# extract wss for 2-15 clusters
wss_values <- map_dbl(k.values, wss)
## Warning: did not converge in 10 iterations

## Warning: did not converge in 10 iterations
plot(k.values, wss_values,
     type="b", pch = 19, frame = FALSE, 
     xlab="Number of clusters K",
     ylab="Total within-clusters sum of squares")

The elbow plot indicates that the optimal k size may fall within 3 to 6 clusters. Below are plots for 3-6 clusters.

# plot k= 3, 4,5,6,
seg.cptk3 <- kmeans(cpnumfta, centers=3, nstart = 25)
seg.cptk4 <- kmeans(cpnumfta, centers=4, nstart = 25)
seg.cptk5 <- kmeans(cpnumfta, centers=5, nstart = 25)
seg.cptk6 <- kmeans(cpnumfta, centers=6, nstart = 25)

# plots to compare
p1 <- fviz_cluster(seg.cptk3, geom = "point", data = cpnumfta) + ggtitle("k = 3")
p2 <- fviz_cluster(seg.cptk4, geom = "point",  data = cpnumfta) + ggtitle("k = 4")
p3 <- fviz_cluster(seg.cptk5, geom = "point",  data = cpnumfta) + ggtitle("k = 5")
p4 <- fviz_cluster(seg.cptk6, geom = "point",  data = cpnumfta) + ggtitle("k = 6")

Further analysis on the mean response to the survey questions is needed to understand the customer profiles of each cluster.

#Convert k = 3 to original scale, use original cpnumft dataframe and group by cluster
#to produce a table with the mean values of each cluster to allow for further
#analysis on each cluster.
cptk3con <- cpnumft %>%
  mutate(Cluster = seg.cptk3$cluster) %>%
  group_by(Cluster) %>%
  summarise_all("mean")

print(cptk3con, width = Inf) #print entire cluster and questions tibble

Since the fviz_cluster function includes running Principle Components Analysis, it’s good to understand which variables contribute to the explained variances.

#Run PCA on cpnumfta to see the variables that contribute to dim1 & dim2
P <- prcomp(cpnumfta, scale = FALSE)   #prcomp is pca function
fviz_eig(P, addlabels = TRUE)  #visualize the top dimensions

#Dimensions 1 & 2 combined explain 24.3% of the variances

fviz_contrib(P, choice = "var", axes = 1, top = 6) # Top 6 contributors to the first component

fviz_contrib(P, choice = "var", axes = 2, top = 6)# Top 6 contributors to the 2nd component

Customer Profiles from the 3 Clusters

Distinct customer profiles can be derived by analyzing the mean values from the variables with the highest contributions to Dim1 & Dim2. The variables with the highest contributions included:
* The frequency of using social media sites like Twitter (q13r2), MySpace (q13r3)
* Usage of music sites like AOL Radio (q13r7), Last.fm (q13r8), and Vevo (q13r5 )
* Entertainment interests: “I like learning more about my favorite TV shows when I’m not watching them (q24r8) and”Music is an important part of my life (q24r7)
* “It’s usually worth spending a few extra dollars to get extra app features” (q26r12)
* “People often ask my advice when they are looking to buy technology or electronic products” (q24r2)

The three customer segments derived were:
* Low Engagers
* Social Entertainers
* Social Observers

All three segments exhibited high usage of Facebook, so usage of other social media sites in addition to Facebook was a key differentiator between the segments.

Low Engagers had low usage of other social media sites as well as low usage of music sites. While they had a medium level of interest in music, they had a low interest in paying for apps features.

Social Entertainers had higher usage of Twitter and MySpace than Social Observers as well asl higher usage of music sites. This segment also had a high interest in paying for app features.

Social Observers were differentiated in their higher usage of other social media sites but low usage of music sites. They did have a high interest in music, indicating that they may be potentially interested in a new music app.

From the higher usage of social media and music sites and the highest interest in paying for app features, the Social Entertainers segment has the highest potential to be interested in the social entertainment app. The Social Observers segment also shows potential interest, but may be more casual users. The Low Engagers have low potential to be interested in the app and should not be pursued.
